did.unittitle: Sealantic Fund records

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The objective of the Sealantic Fund was to serve as a special purpose, grant making foundation. While the fund donated money for a variety of purposes, its most significant effort was in the furthering of the education of the American Protestant clergy. The importance of theological education at this time was heightened due to the recent conclusion of World War II.

Although the advancement of theological education was the central component of the Sealantic Fund, attention was also paid to historical preservation in Westchester County, NY. Following the shortage of competent nurses after World War II, the education of nurses in America also became a central issue to the Sealantic Fund.
The collection spans from the early 1940s to the later 1970s, following the merger of the Sealantic Fund into the greater Rockefeller Brothers Fund.

acqinfo.head: Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: The Rockefeller Brothers Fund deposited the records of the Sealantic Fund at the Rockefeller Archive Center. The RAC received the collections in several accessions in 1979.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: The Rockefeller Archive Center has title to the collection and has authority to grant permission to cite and publish archival material from the collection. Rockefeller Brothers Fund retains copyright and literary rights in the Sealantic Fund collection, in so far as it holds them.
Requests to publish long excerpts from a report, a copyrighted publication, or the report(s)/publication(s) in its entirety will be referred to the officers of the Rockefeller Brothers Fund.

bioghist.head: Institutional History
bioghist.p: The Sealantic Fund (SF), one of the lesser known philanthropies of John D. Rockefeller, Jr., was established and funded in 1938 to serve as a special purpose, grant making foundation. Although seemingly referencing a maritime corporation, the term Sealantic stems from a purpose dear to the heart of early Rockefeller generations: theology. The name arose from a combination of two churches located in the primary residences of JDR, Jr.--Seal Harbor, Maine ("seal") and Pocantico Hills, New York ("antic"). As its name references, the SF was not a private institution, but rather a fund used to support a variety of philanthropic purposes.

The SF was incorporated on November 19, 1938 in New York City. On the day of its incorporation, JDR, Jr., who was neither an incorporator nor a trustee, gifted 300 shares of Socony-Vacuum Stick (worth $3,637) to SF--a gift he contributed annually until his death. When he cerated the foundation, JDR, JR. stated that his prime purpose in establishing the fund was to provide over a period of years continuing support of the Pocantico Hills Union Church and the Mount Desert Larger Parish in Tarrytown, New York and Mount Desert, Maine respectively. In addition, JDR, Jr. ordered that the SF carry out any other philanthropic work that he believed deserved monetary support.

Although the SF accomplished a variety of purposes throughout its thirty-five year history, its most significant effort was a program created to further the education of the American Protestant clergy. This program would shape the existence of Protestantism in America after World War II. Following the tendency of the Rockefellers towards religious interests, another influential project began by the SF was the creation of America's first center for churches of numerous denominations. One important focus of the fund was that of historical restoration and preservation. The SF was responsible for dispersing funds for the restoration of numerous historic properties (specifically Sunnyside and Philipse Castle) in the Sleepy Hollow area of the Hudson Valley. The education of those both near and far soon became an issue. The SF chose to dedicate their time and money to enriching theological education abroad and nursing education at home.

The SF allowed JDR, Jr. to realize one of his oldest dreams: the agreement of Christian denominations in America to work together under one organization. JDR, JR., under the instrument of the SF, was financially responsible for creating the symbol of this unity--the building of the national headquarters (the Interchurch Center) on Riverside Drive.

The most substantial work during the existence of the SF occurred in the field of education, specifically in improving the education of Protestant ministers. Following a remarkable donation by JDR, Jr. of $20 million to improve the state of American Protestantism, the SF embarked on a thirty-five year reformation. It was decided that half of the donation would be used to further the existence of of six Protestant institutions--Vanderbilt, University of Chicago, Berkeley, Yale, Union Theological Semianry, Harvard--believed to be crucial to the strengthening of Protestantism. At this time, an additional $725,000 was donated to the American Association of Theological Schools because it was deemed necessary that the field of Protestant education have a central, professional organization to set and maintain standards. This substantial gift was followed, in 1957, by a gift to the International Missionary Council to fund the world's "younger churches" (those in Asia, Africa, and Latin America). This donation would culminate in the creation of the Theological Education Fund.

After receiving criticism for choosing only six seminaries to fund, the next move of the SF was to contribtue money to a range of seminaries, many of them less well known. This act helped to promote consolidation and mutual assistance in the seminary field. Following this announcement, SF received a letter from Morehouse University asking for support in the creation of America's first Theological education center composed of churches from numerous denominations. In 1959, the Interdenomiantional Theological Center was created. The success of the center led the SF to support further consolidation efforts, this time on America's West Coast. This new federation, the Graduate Theological Union, was formed in 1961 and was composed of five seminaries across California. After monitoring the Union for three years, the SS approved requests from the Graduate Theological Union to fund the creation of new facilities. Further donations were made to institutions modeled after the programs incorproated at the Interdenomiantional Theological Center and the Graduate Theological Union. The programs included the Boston Theological Institute, the Richmond Theological Center, and the Rochester Center for Theological Studies.

Once the SF felt that they had provided for American seminaries to the best of their abilities, their attention shifted to the basic component of providing ministers with a higher education. Approximately $5 million went towards the creation of fellowship grants administered under five separate program: Sealantic's Faculty Fellowships, the Protestant Fellowship Program, the Rockefeller Doctorial Fellowships Black Doctorial Candidates in Religion, the Parish Ministers Fellowship Program, and the Library Fellowship Program.

The final steps taken by the SF in Theological education was: first, the decision to provide the American Theological Library Association with a substantial grant, and second, the decision to fund the Case Study Institute. This last decision arose following the realization that many in the field believed that current educational courses were outdated--this institute was created to find a way to add innovation to the field of Theological education.

The SF contibuted to numerous organizations beyond the world of Theology. The most notable role of the SF outside Theological work was its use as a special instrument for the holding and operation of properties, ranging from a residence for young women on stage (the Rehearsal Club) to historically important properties such as Sunnyside. Sealantic's first substantial project outside Theology was the purchase and restoration of the Hudson River estate, Sunnyside--the home of Washington Irving, the first American Author of international fame. Following this purchase, the SF purchased two other properties which, alongside Irving's Sunnyside, made up Sleepy Hollow Restorations (on whose board many SF employees served). The conclusion of Sealantic Fund's connection with historical restoration was its purchase of Carter's Grove in 1964 (by 1969, the SF transferred ownership to Colonial Williamsburg).

A unique part of the SF history arose during the shortage of trained nurses in the mid-1950s and 1960s. The nursing program created by the SF ran from 1957 until 1970 (when it was taken over by the RBF). The significance of the program can be seen in the following three areas: their role in the growth of two-year college nurisng schools, and their support to registered nurses in receiving professional nurisng degrees and to students of disadvantaged minorities in entering nurisng schools. In the eyes of the SF, the creation of this program was a response to a crisis where private money was required. It was considered to be solely in the fields of education and social welfare.
The SF merged with the Rockefeller Brothers Fund in 1971.
